,Recommended,287340,11497611,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,a.stent,"I have only played 37 mins (according to Steam) so this is an initial review for anyone, like me, who could not resist getting an old Colin McRae Rally on Steam. It certainly feels similar to playing the old game, and I feel like I recognise the tracks from my days spent on CM1 and 2.0. I would hesitantly recommend this as I have enjoyed my first few runs on it. However, there are a few issues. I have struggled to get my controller to behave as I would like. I can select keys or buttons but cannot change the analogue stick. Consequently I have to push left to accelerate and right to brake. I had a few hairpins where I ""whacked on the brake"" and actually accelerated into a crash. Also crests appear to cause my car to roll over several times. The next issue is the ""difficulty"". While getting used to the controller I decided to do the first Championship consisting of six tracks. Despite my crashes and rolls I won with a total of just under 19 minutes with the second place getting just under 26 minutes. I really ought to have to at least get good before winning, and never by that much!However, I enjoyed playing and it felt nostalgic. I certainly like the idea of some old classics being ""remastered"" for modern computers, and at a good price too. I look forward to a remastered Cannon Fodder... (hint hint)"
